%N A395531 Lay down bricks of length 1, 2, 3, ... on the top-right quadrant of the x-y plane. Place a brick as close to x=0 as possible, and on the highest row with bricks directly underneath where the new brick does not overhang. a(n) is the length of the leftmost brick on each row.
%C A395531 Positions of 0's in A233380. - _Rémy Sigrist_, Apr 30 2026
%C A395531 Conjecture: when n = a(m) for some m, we have a(n) = n(n+3)/2 - m. Verified experimentally up to m=1172, n=688491. - _Aleksei Udovenko_, May 07 2026
%H A395531 Aleksei Udovenko, <a href="/A395531/b395531.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A395531 Aleksei Udovenko, <a href="/A395531/a395531.cpp.txt">Optimized C++ program</a>
%e A395531 After 11 bricks have been placed, the wall looks like this (with A for block 10 and B for block 11):
%e A395531   BBBBBBBBBBB---------
%e A395531   7777777AAAAAAAAAA---
%e A395531   333666666999999999--
%e A395531   12244445555588888888
%e A395531 The next brick, 12 units long, has to go on the bottom row because on any other row it would have to overhang the row below.
%o A395531 (Python)
%o A395531 from itertools import count
%o A395531 def a(): # Generator function for the sequence
%o A395531     rows = []
%o A395531     height = 0
%o A395531     for n in count(1):
%o A395531         if height==0 or n <= rows[height-1]:
%o A395531             yield n
%o A395531             height += 1
%o A395531             rows.append(n)
%o A395531         else:
%o A395531             for i in range(height-1,-1,-1):
%o A395531                 if i==0 or rows[i] + n <= rows[i-1]:
%o A395531                     rows[i] += n
%o A395531                     break
%Y A395531 Cf. A233380.
%K A395531 easy,nonn,new
%O A395531 1,2
%A A395531 _Christian Perfect_, Apr 27 2026
